title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger Speed Six
postcontent:
For Sale or Trade is my 1976 Ruger Speed Six in Stainless Steel, and chambered in .357 Magnum

In 1972, Sturm Ruger introduced their line of "Double Action" revolvers. This line consisted of the Security Six, Service Six, and the Speed Six, all of which were marketed with Law Enforcement, Military, and Civil Defense in mind. They became very well known for their dependability and durability. Essentially, they were built to take a beating and withstand much abuse.

This line of revolvers marked the way for Sturm Ruger's entry into the Double Action revolver market. As with all Ruger firearms, the Speed Six revolvers were robustly designed with large, heavy-duty parts. The First Stainless Steel version was shipped in 1975. Although I am a big fan of S&W Revolvers, I believe that this line of Ruger Revolvers, that were directly created to compete with Smith & Wesson, are more robust and have a slightly stronger barrel shank with larger and stronger internal parts. It was one of the first designed revolvers to use a hammer that was powered by a coil spring which directly created the "Transfer-Bar firing system. One of the distinguishing features of this line of revolver from Ruger is, the simplicity of the design and the ability to break the weapon down with just the use of a small flathead screwdriver, coin, or cartridge casing.

This Speed Six revolver has not been abused and was shipped from the factory in 1976. It is "Pre-Warning Roll Marks" which were on all modern Ruger Barrels that followed. It is 100% original and comes complete with original "Red" Ruger box, and owner’s manual. I am not the original owner so I cannot speak of “Round Count” but I will say that it does not appear to have been fired much and looks as it may have spent the majority of its life in a safe.

Features,
* 2-3/4" Barrel Length
* 6 Shot Fluted Cylinder
* Single / Double Action
* True Stainless Steel Finish
* Serrated, Ramped Front Sight
* Integrated Rear Sight to prevent Snagging

title: For Sale:  JUST REDUCED FROM $950/ Springfield Model 1873 Trap Door
postcontent:
THIS IS A PART OF AMERICAN HISTORY! OWN IT!
The Springfield Model 1873 was the first breech loaded rifle adopted by the U.S. Military.
This infantry model in .45-70-Gov't was owned by my great grandfather who served the Union Army in the Signal Corps during the Civil War.
The Springfield 1873 design was chosen for service from approximately 100 MFG's rifles submitted to the Army.
The single shot "Trap Door" design was chosen for its reliability even over faster repeating designs which tended to jam more readily. A recruit could load & shoot 8 rounds/minute while an expert infantryman about 16/minute.
The rifles were later used in the Spanish/American War and as buffalo rifles.
This rifle is in good shape with minor nicks & scratches on the stock & forend.
The U.S., U.S. Springfield, Eagle emblem, Serial Number (139949), & Model No. are clearly visible on the barrel, breech mechanisms, & butt plate.
